      "id": "game_29_kramnik_shirov",
      "title": "Game 29: Kramnik vs Shirov (Bundesliga 1992)",
      "description": "Illustrative Game for The Sämisch Variation. Black sacrifices a pawn with 6...c5, leading to active piece play and an eventual draw.",
      "textContext": "Page 82-83 of Starting Out: The King's Indian",
      "preparsedJson": {
        "game_id": "game_29",
        "white": "Kramnik",
        "black": "Shirov",
        "event": "Bundesliga 1992",
        "initial_moves": "d4 Nf6 c4 g6 Nc3 Bg7 e4 d6 f3 O-O Be3 c5 dxc5 dxc5 Qxd8 Rxd8 Bxc5 Nc6",
        "interactive_section": {
          "starting_move": 10,
          "moves": [
            {
              "move_number": 10,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Ba3",
              "commentary": "With the black queen gone, White has less to fear from ...Nb4, so he can afford to develop this bishop. Note that the alternative 10 Nd5 is the subject of Game 30."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 10,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "a5!",
              "commentary": "This is a key move, preparing to establish a knight on b4. Black must react quickly before White has time to consolidate. For example, if Black instead plays 10...b6? 11 Nd5 Nxd5 12 cxd5 Nb4 13 Rc1 Nxa2 14 Rc7 and White maintains his extra pawn with an active position."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 11,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Rd1",
              "commentary": "White tries to challenge the d-file. On 11 Nd5 Nxd5 12 cxd5 Nb4 13 O-O-O e6! is fine for Black."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 11,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "Be6",
              "commentary": "This is better than exchanging on d1 as that would only help the white king to a better home on the queenside."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 12,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Nd5",
              "commentary": ""
            },
            {
              "move_number": 12,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "Nb4!",
              "commentary": "(Diagram 4) The logic behind ...Nb4 is not difficult to understand. Black has a massive lead in development so he seeks to complicate the game before White can consolidate. There is also the little matter of ...Nc2+ on the cards, which will deprive White of his dark-squared bishop and ruin his pawn structure."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 13,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Nxe7+",
              "commentary": "13 Bd3 Bxd5 14 cxd5 Nxd3+ 15 Rxd3 e6 is not dangerous for Black, while lines that White should definitely avoid are 13 Nxb4 Rxd1+ 14 Kxd1 axb4 15 Bxb4 Rxa2 and 13 Bxb4?! axb4 14 Nxb4 Nd7! 15 Rd2 Nc5, as in both cases his position is on the verge of collapsing."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 13,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "Kh8",
              "commentary": ""
            },
            {
              "move_number": 14,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Rxd8+",
              "commentary": "White can also keep rooks on the board with 14 Nd5. Play will develop along similar lines, e.g. 14...Nc2+ 15 Kf2 Nxa3 16 bxa3 b5!."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 14,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "Rxd8",
              "commentary": ""
            },
            {
              "move_number": 15,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Nd5",
              "commentary": "White is two pawns up but miles behind in development. He will now try and complete his development under the cover of his one good piece, the knight on d5. If Black takes the knight then White will recapture cxd5 and obtain a strong passed pawn."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 15,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "Nc2+",
              "commentary": "Black starts with the obvious move."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 16,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Kd2",
              "commentary": "This walks into a pin but neither can White claim an advantage with 16 Kf2. After 16...Nxa3 17 bxa3 b5! Shirov gave 18 Nh3 Rc8 Shirov gave 19 Nhf4 with equality."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 16,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "Nxa3",
              "commentary": ""
            },
            {
              "move_number": 17,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "bxa3",
              "commentary": ""
            },
            {
              "move_number": 17,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "b5!",
              "commentary": "This is the star undermining move. White's control of d5 is soon to be history."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 18,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Nh3",
              "commentary": "Draw agreed. A draw was agreed in view of the variation 18...bxc4 19 Bxc4 Nxd5 20 exd5 Bxd5 21 Bxd5 Rxd5+ (Diagram 5). The strong bishop certainly compensates for the useless extra a-pawn."
            }
          ]
